comments.text:
My dude, I don't play or really care about esports, including Smash Bros. But you got me hooked and here I am, an hour into a documentary on a game I only vaguely knew about, focused on a person I hadn't heard of simply due to not knowing the game-- and I'm sitting here totally loving Mang0 like nobody's business! 

This video is my main source of any info so my opinion isn't fully formed since I'd need to do a lot more research to get a full picture and to minimize chance of bias (like how someone watching that first video you mentioned would have unknowingly been super biased if they only knew any info from that. 

But I have to say, based on Mang0's background, all the clips of him and his friends, the choices he made along the way both in terms of which characters to choose and why, and especially his real life choices-- and on top of that, the sportsmanship he seems to have.... I don't think I've ever respected anyone in any sports whether traditional or e-, than I do this dude right now. 

Granted, I don't like sports so I could be missing someone-- but I also randomly watch videos or learn from others or read about things I don't care for just because I still find it interesting to understand what everyone else sees. And regardless of my personal interest, we are all human and it's still impressive or educational to learn about others.

At least based on an hour in at 59:00 (because I guess I don't know what is coming so it's possible my view would do a 180 by the end), I gotta say: 

A large reason I don't like sports (aside from just generally having no interest in the games themselves) is the tendency toward egoism and Othering within the players and fans. Fans get WAY tf too invested in their team, especially traditional in person ones, to the point that what should be a fun experience where prowess can be showcased and everyone can respect it in the end, instead easily can turn into toxicity, fights and injuries, and at the very least a completely unnecessary dichotomization of similarly minded people. 

And then the players themselves in traditional sports especially get treated like gods when they aren't, and they get paid way tf too much. But the game itself is also unfair to them because for so many people, time is against them. And they only have a couple decades at best to try to do all they can to "prove" themselves and to make money and a name, before they get thrown aside with a body that's been utterly destroyed in its prime by the very game that sustained it. 

Not always the case of course but it just feels like that can be a common theme. 

And the whole time, money is being wielded in both the foreground and background as a means to at "best" translate a human being to a number to quantify their "value", and at worst is maiming, threatening, and even killing the players themselves as they become nothing more than a pawn for those in power of money, and they are expected and at times forced to play unfairly in the interest of someone else's pocket. (I'm thinking of that South American soccer/futbol player who was known as the gentleman and seemingly this great guy and fantastic player who was murdered because of one accidental point loss for his team)

I have no respect for that entire situation. It's not helpful on any level that it just encourages people to assign their identity to whatever they play or watch, and especially within the fandom that can lead to toxicity. (Your video on Lindsey Jacobellis is a perfect example of that-- btw, that's what YouTube randomly recommended me and I also don't care about snowboarding but I watched that video, and was so impressed by your style that I checked out your channel itself and that led me here).

At any rate, what I'm saying is my experience so far has been mixed on many levels for sports in all contexts, and I do know for sure there are great people involved as fans and as players etc... The issue I see is less the people themselves individually necessarily and more the greater community and setup as a whole. 

It's a vicious cycle where the toxicity breeds and feeds on itself and, if not held in check by the industry or teams or fan communities themselves, can turn what should be a fun competition on the field into a life defining war on and off the field.

But Mang0 is exactly the type of person and exactly the sort of representation of sports that, if everyone were like him and the greater smash bros community I'm seeing portrayed here, would make sports be what I think fans THINK it is but often isn't.

He's exactly the type of person that I think as a total outsider IS completely legit to get behind, and who ultimately plays the game at the very heart for the fun or skill of it. 

The fact that he made tough but wise choices multiple times in his life to step back to explore something more consistent in order to help his financial situation, and that when he came back he doesn't seem like he was a douche about it, and that he still left again in order to support his family and even his comment in that one video about being able to take his girlfriend to Red Lobster now that he won.... It's some of the most wholesome and endearing things I've seen in any top sports person. 

And even where I paused to leave this comment... That Chillin guy looked so defeated by that 5-0 game, and seeing that clip where Mang0 stood up to back him up, while doing so in a really friendly and sportsmanship-focused way, and especially seeing the complete transformation on Chillin's face from that simple act of Mang0's plus the rival having a big smile too.... That is the epitome of what sports SHOULD be. And if all sports WERE like this, I would have way more respect for it and feel less frustrated by its prominence because it would be showcasing good behaviors and the best way for people to be able to be at odds with each other in friendly competitions while still having respect for all. 

I also REALLY love how he chose and played his characters based on what was interesting and challenging to him... The way he challenged and changed the very understanding of some of the characters themselves, and especially how he challenged himself to adjust and adapt to the greater societal context of the game and community at different times. 

To me, that's someone who's playing for all the right reasons so I would already love him. But given his background in a rough neighborhood being raised by a single mom, and his prowess in both physical and online sports, and his dedication that kept him from danger like gangs (which was not an easy task no doubt), it already would have garnered a higher level of respect from me. 

But then you add into it that he's genuinely freaking incredible at the game and it's like -- WOW, this guy is so impressive and commendable!

The fact that he became best friends with his biggest rival back home says everything I believe could ever be said about his integrity and just who he is altogether as a sports player of any kind. And the fact that he thought of his family first every step of the way says everything you could ever need to know about who he is at heart as a human being. 

Insofar as where I've paused: Mang0 my dude, I freaking love you ❤

comments.text:
Aight paused before the real meat at 7:00, let's talk EmpLemon.  "Shadow of his former self" and questioning his God status is far too hyperbolic, I'll give you that much.  That being said, there was plenty of reason to think Mango was in an awkward spot even going into 2020, let's begin

-Mango goes 18 months without a major win, Smashcon 2017-GOML 2019
Stat speaks for itself, but there's a bit more there.  Plup, Mew2King, and Zain collect their first supermajors at Genesis 5, Smash Summit 6, and Shine 2018 during this period of Mango being winless

-Waning placements and 2018 Ranking
Mew2King has a far superior year with his first supermajor and an average finish of 5.3 for the year in 10 tournaments, while Mango's average finish was 9.7 in 11.  Some would say counting his 65th place exit in pools at Smashcon is unfair since he dropped out after getting wobbled...to which I say he had the choice to continue, but chose to buster out and start stroking his dick on Twitter.  Yet come the 2018 ranking Mango gets ranked above M2K highlighting bias that everyone knows exists but never gets addressed.  Hell Zain collected an average of 6.1 and his first win, so there's good reason to put him above Mango as well

-2019 Tournaments
This is more open to discourse, but is worth visiting.  2019 saw Mango take three tournaments, GOML 2019, Big House 9, and Birthday Bash.  In the case of Big House 9 there's nothing to argue, he beat the best player in Hbox, beat Leffen in the runback, and vanquished his demon in Zain twice. In the case of GOML he had to go through SFAT and Axe, both of which have miserable records against Mango, but he did have to knock out Leffen to do so.  With Birthday Bash it's less noticeable, but he did dodge Plup/Hbox in WF and instead got Hax$ who he has a commanding set lead over, but given he did overcome Zain and Hbox this is more of a lucky break than a favorable bracket.

-Godly Expectations
Simply put he's in the situation Hbox is in right now.  You go from being Top 3 and winning routinely to a sudden drought and major losses while others move past you.  This at the time while Armada, Leffen, Plup, and Mew2King were routinely collecting major wins while Hbox collected a staggering 15 in that drought period, you begin to ask if something is wrong.  

-Awkward Change in Guard
2018-2019 was hectic with talent entering and exiting.  Armada and Mew2King exiting, Axe/Wizzrobe coming into their prime, iBDW/Zain/Hax$ were still coming up (BOXX Hax I should stress), and Smash Ult releasing with some players like Leffen dividing time between it and Melee.  A supermajor win is a supermajor win, but the talent pool was still recovering from the exit of two Gods.  This is shown in some reputable people declaring Hbox had No. 1 on lock shortly after the Summer rankings posted due to Wizzrobe's absence after CEO and Axe's decline

-Hindsight is 2020
If you told me that Hbox would narrowly make Top 5 in 2022 or that Mango following THAT Smash Summit victory and strong presence in the online era would be ranked out the Top 10 for Summer 2022 I'd call you a damn liar.  Similarly if you told me after a convincing Smash Con 2017 that Mango would not win for 18 months, I'd be visibly confused.  A former TO turned NASCAR-tuber has a saying "Celebrate every win like it's your last, because it might be" and as time progresses you wonder if they will return to collect another.  2018 had some hope like the Smash Summit Mew2King won, as Mango went 3-0 in pools, only to get upset by Zain again and exit 7th in a heartbreak.  Seeing him collect the W at GOML 2019 felt similar to Isai winning Smash 64 at Smashcon 2023 last year, a feeling of relief to see them finally collect another 1st place after so much time

Naturally now it feels silly to have doubted him.  When I saw him ranked 11th for Summer 2022 I thought back to 2018 and said it's too soon to give up, if anything it may motivate him more to grab a win and shortly after he did just that and won three more to finish 3rd on the year.  I only post this because while I do think Lemon's minimizing Mango went too far, those 18 months were a grueling time to be alive.  There's a reason a video called "The End of Mangogelion" exists

























Also I take more offense at Lemon comparing Hax's video to Content Cop than the actual contents of the video itself.  Sorry but dumb ranting about Dark Triads and Fascist posting don't change the awful ban worthy things Leffen has done

This is amazing. When you got to Summit 11, the way you've told the story really made it feel like a celebration. The "if there's a chance of victory, I'll have to take it!" attitude from Mango's interview, the comradely between the old gods, and that cut where Mango's down on the last game for a quote about the Buddha? Wild. Absolutely wild. 
One of the things about Empleon's video was that it recognized it was biased, but it was in service of a better story. In that video, the narrative for Hungrybox was that he was a constant, overlooked but always there, a benchmark that never wavered. Which was great, but it also was kind of lonely; a St. Peter forever posted at the gates. 
The best description for this video is like the return of a king. Mango, through refinement of talent and hard work, was the young face of the community, bohemian and enthralling. But then came that slump in the late 10's, and he stumbles and falters. But then he comes back and fights, he comes back and wins, and at Summit 11, when the stakes are the highest they've ever been? Mango reminds everyone that a God doesn't die.
The last time I've played any Smash game was when Obama was President, and as a player I just don't think I'm suited for it. What can I say, some people have skills and fighting games just ain't one of mine. But watching these matches, watching these videos, gives me an appreciation of how strong the community is. So thank you; for showing the world what these games can be.

comments.text: What I like most about Mang0's story is not necessarily his own performances, though some were very impressive. Nor is it his long-lasting memetic impact on the game, though the Pavlovian "that's not safe" utterances from commentators every time a Falco double lasers from ledge still get a chuckle out of me. It's the fact that he played Melee in a way that was the most emblematic of the platonic ideal of Melee: fast-paced, aggressive, with plenty of custom combos and (especially in his earlier days) hard reads. While the technical proficiency of some other players were higher than him, and there were others known for being even more stylish, none blended the two together in the exact right combination to be able to stand in the pantheon despite never memorizing the numbers like M2K did, never flowcharted and practiced the optimal punish game like Armada did, nor taking the absolute most advantage possible out of degenerate game mechanics with the will to take on any amount of hate like Hungrybox did. PPMD also was a lot like this, but with all love to PP, we know his story is that of a candle burning at both ends, insanely bright for a while but ultimately burning out. (I'm glad he's doing a lot better health-wise nowadays!) Mang0 represents the spirit of every amateur player out there–from newbies to vets–who plays because they just love how sick Melee is. None of the five gods of melee are, on a personal level, heroes. Just like everyone else on earth, they have flaws. Nonetheless, Mang0's flaws–both in gameplay and in personality–are just right for the kind of game that Melee itself is: flawed, but sick as hell. Even in the modern era of rectangles and phobs and dweens and UCF, with people optimizing the game to ridiculous levels, even without M2K there to be the emblem of "optimal" play, you can't ever count the revival-age spirit that Mang0 represents out. He's influenced so many players and the metagame itself. Zain playing Roy with an obviously-fake sock puppet handle is the modern echoes of Scorpadorp. I hope that even when Mang0 eventually retires for good, people will still keep that spirit alive in this immortal game.

I think the problem with the EmpLemon video was just that he locked himself into a very specific format when it comes to the narrative.

The Never Ever videos are by design meant to shine a light on what the author feels is the greatest of something. The Hbox video, which I still love, is surely flawed due to this format and you did an incredible job at explaining why. Melee has just such a volatile competitive scene where literally anyone can come out of nowhere and be the best if they put in the time and work. Both Zain and especially aMSa literally prove that. Emp really should've just consulted first with people in the Melee community before making his video. I dont think that Emp shouldn't have made the Hbox documentary (it was clearly needed given how Leffen was mobilizing Twitter against him), but it probably shouldn't have been a Never Ever video.

THAT BEING SAID, it was made during a period in time where Mang0 had just left his biggest rut and was being outshined by Hbox. I can kind of understand Emp's rationale, but historically, Mang0 was just never this consistent machine like M2K, Armada or Zain. Hell, neither was Hbox (which really shows Emp's bias). Its because of that why people considered Armada to be the GOAT for such a long time, and that narrative is only really changing because A: Zain just set this entirely new standard for what it takes to be the best, and B: players like Mang0, Leffen and Hbox are able to still stick it out and prove they have what it takes despite having been playing this game for so long now (even if Leffen hasnt been playing for as long as the other two, and as much as I hate the little prick, its undisputable that he's still been playing at a top level for nearly a decade now and that can't be ignored).

I think that the gaff in that throw-away line really is something that people get way too upset about. I don't think the thesis of it was "hbox is the last god" more, so it was about trying to explore why melee fans hated hungrybox so much more than any of their top players. I think the backlash from the community after seeing that mang0 got discredited and completely disregarding the video almost certainly proves some validity to that statement. It's very clear that it was a video made by an outsider, who probably wasn't aware that mang0 bustering for a year or two was just par for the course, so when they saw something that reinforced their narrative of Juan being the clear best player in the world, they just ran with it. I think the line was trying to point out how no one could really contend with him on an eye to eye level, rather than Mang0 should have his God status revoked because he lost to magi and Fizzwiggle.

Also, yeah, that Hax tweet was weird, but you can't deny the first  evidence.zip happened, and that hax, as a victim of those abuses, may have seen more attacks than there really was. The presentation of that video was terrible, but we could have at least taken his own post leffen ban experiences at face value when assessing if the charges had any validity. I'm not Emp's PR guy by any means, but that's what I took away from those 2 statements.

comments.text:
@andychen5447  There's a few I can remember off the top of my head.

 For one he made a very odd argument claiming that Peach was essentially exactly the same as Puff to make a point that playing a pink floaty character is only cool when Armada does it but not Hbox. The better approach would be explaining Puff's role in the cast and how a puff is optimally played in order to achieve top level results, which still takes a lot of skill and hard work, and which was something he was doing through the video. But then he goes and says this which basically deconstructs Emp's entire argument and makes it seem like he doesn't really have that much in depth knowledge about Melee's roster.

He also claims mang0's god status was in serious contention, which honestly might have been more bad timing because he released the video a few day after mang0 won another major after a stretch of no major wins. But he does it in a way to claim that hbox was the only true remaining god which is a statement that definitely didn't age well. Since the release of that video Hbox and mang0 basically have the same major win rate, if not a little more in mang0's favor. mang0 will always be a god and mang0 will always be able to win, same as hbox.

There are a few more I can't recall, I would have to give the video a good watch again as it's been a while. The main issue with EmpLemon's video is that it was a gateway for a lot of people to get into the Melee scene, but it was a video constructed to be more entertainment than it was to be a factual or accurate representation of the Melee scene. That's not inherently a bad thing, EmpLemon is an entertaining video creator, however it gives a lot of brand new people a skewed outlook coming into Melee for the first time. There are a couple common inaccurate beliefs I see perpetuated among his and newer players that get traced back to EmpLemon's video.
